<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910222-0102</DOCNO><DOCID>910222-0102.</DOCID><HL>   ATandamp;T Cuts Phone Rates   For U.S. Troops in Mideast   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>02/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   T MDEST</CO><IN>TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)</IN><GV>FEDERAL COMMUNICATIONS COMMISSION (FCC)</GV><LP>   Troops in the Mideast who have been receivingunprecedented front-line telephone service got a break ontheir phone bills.   American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co., after numerouscustomer complaints and expression of concern from theFederal Communications Commission staff about steep phonebills for Mideast-based calls, cut its rates from SaudiArabia to the U.S. about 30%. ATandamp;T's cut follows a similarmove last week by MCI Communications Corp.</LP><TEXT>   Over the past two weeks, the FCC staff has met with allthree long-distance carriers serving the Mideast to urgelower rates on calls to the U.S. and continuity of servicefor military families behind on the bills.   Frank Ianna, ATandamp;T vice president of marketing,international communications services, said ATandamp;T, whichcarries most of the traffic from the Mideast, cut its ratesafter receiving &quot;enough complaints about phone bills to bealarmed.&quot; He said the new rates could cause the company tolose some $3 million a month, based on current traffic fromthe region. Since September, the company has been providingfree facsimile services to families of U.S. militarypersonnel and has installed about 1,500 telephones linked bysatellites on the desert front.</TEXT></DOC>